&gt; Does this show you what I mean?
&gt; 
&gt; public class AllTests {
&gt; 
&gt;     @Decorate(class=com.foo.WrapTestsInAdapterBeforeRunning.class)
&gt;     public static Test suite() throws Exception {
&gt;         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt;         suite.addTestSuite(ConfigurationTest.class);
&gt;         suite.addTest(FunctionalTests.suite());
&gt;         suite.addTest(UnitAndDatabaseTests.suite());
&gt;         return suite;
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; However, after giving this more thought I realized that we could do 
&gt; something easier without using the decorator annotations.  We use a 
&gt; modified junix.util.DirectorySuiteBuilder to build the 
&gt; individual suites 
&gt; referenced in the previous example.  Within that class we could 
&gt; determine that we are running with JUnit4 and wrap the class with the 
&gt; adapter /as/ we add it to the suite instead of trying to decorate it 
&gt; later.  So, I guess my idea blows up in my face -- but at 
&gt; least it blew 
&gt; up early in the cycle!
